nner spiritual struggle. This judiciously balanced, accessibly written, and highly relevant book looks closely at a range of sources from sacred Islamic texts to modern interpretations, opening a critically important perspective on the role of Islam in the contemporary world. David Cook cites from scriptural, legal, and newly translated texts to give readers insight into the often ambiguous information that is used to construct Islamic doctrine. He sheds light on legal developments relevant to fighting and warfare and places the internal, spiritual jihad within the larger context of Islamic religion. He describes some of the conflicts that occur in radical groups and shows how the more mainstream supporters of these groups have come to understand and justify violence. He has also included a special appendix of relevant documents including materials related to the September 11 attacks and published manifestos issued by Usama b. Ladin and Palestinian suicide-martyrs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIslamy21st century. 0aIslamic fundamentalism. 0aJihad. 0aWarxReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh  aal qaida.  aarab spring.  acaliphate.  acontemporary islam.  adefense of islam.  aglobalist radical islam.  agreater jihad.  aholy war.  aisil.  aisis.  aislam.  aislamic doctrine.  aislamic extremism.  aislamic fundamentalism.  aislamic religion.  aislamic studies.  ajihad ideology.  ajihad theory.  ajihad.  ajihadi culture.  ajihadi states.  ajihadism.  akoran.  alesser jihad.  amuslim radicals.  aquran.  aradical islam.  aradical muslims.  aradicalism.  areligious history.  areligious terrorism.  asalafi jihadi.  aspiritual warfare.  aterrorism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Pres